ce:section.ce:para:
Adsorption efficiency can be enhanced with proximal conditions such as pH, concentration of metal ions and concentration of the materials (OPC and RPC) in the working solution of batch experiments. Hence, adsorption efficiency can be increased by carrying out the following tests. As previously mentioned in the section on fluorescence, the ideal pH setting for adsorption is also thought to be pH 7 (Mansoor and Abbasitabar, 2020). This is to prevent hydrogen ion adsorption in the acidic region and metal ions precipitation as metal hydroxide in the high basic region. Then the concentration of copper and bismuth ions is raised, by maintaining a pH of 7 with a constant adsorbent (OPC, and RPC) dosage of 4 mg/l. As a result, it can be seen that for both OPC and RPC, the adsorption efficiency decreases as the concentration of metal ions increases (Figs. 8(a) and 9(a)

                           ). The absence of adsorption activation sites is the cause of this drop in adsorption efficiency. On the other hand, occupying the activation sites more extensively results in an increase in the adsorption capacity. Lastly, an analysis of the adsorption efficiency is conducted using various OPC:Cu and RPC:Bi ratios, where the adsorption dosage's contribution varies. As seen in Figs. 8(b) and 9(b), the adsorption efficiency rises in this case where there is a greater contribution of adsorbent because of an increase in adsorption activation sites. Comparison of adsorption efficiency with the reported adsorbents is given in Table 2
                           .
